  <title>Brahms at the Piano: Musical Archeology</title>
</head>
  <body bgcolor="white">
                                               
<blockquote>                                                             
       
  <p><b>  <!-- Repeat the line that you added for the <title> tags; this is the heading of the page. -->
       <font face="Verdana" size="4" color="#808080">Brahms at the Piano</font>
      </b></p>
                        <font face="Verdana"> </font><small><font
 face="Verdana" size="3"><small>Sonic archeology: An analysis and transcription
   of the 1889 cylinder  recording of Johannes Brahms performance of a segment
   of his First Hungarian  Dance.<br>
            </small></font><font face="Verdana" size="3"><small><br>
          <br>
          Jonathan Berger (CCRMA, Stanford University) <br>
                       </small></font></small>                          
                              
  <table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" border="0" width="40%">
                       <tbody>
                         <tr>
                           <td valign="top" height="20%" width="20%">   
                                                                        
                                                                  
        <div align="justify">     <font face="Verdana" size="2">        
                                                                        
          </font>                                                       
                
        <pre><big><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="3"
 color="#808080"><big><br>Introduction</big></font></big><br><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"><br></font></big></big></pre>
                                                 
        <div align="justify"><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">On December 
  2<sup>nd</sup> 1889, Theo Wangemann, a representative of <a
 href="http://www-ccrma.stanford.edu/groups/edison/brahms/brahms.html#bios">Thomas 
  Edison</a></font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2"> recorded 
  Johannes Brahms performing two segments of music at the piano.</font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"> The works recorded included part of a paraphrase 
  of Strauss'</font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2"><i> 
  Libelle</i>, preceded by measures 13-72 of Brahms' 1872 arrangement of the
          </font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">first 
 Hungarian Dance for solo piano.</font></big></big><br>
             <big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">While this unique historical 
  document should have been hailed as an important</font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"> 'window' to the world of nineteenth century music 
  performance practices, the</font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"> musical information was almost entirely masked by
noise. The recording was, </font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2">&nbsp;in fact, so noisy that musicologist  Gregor
  Benko wrote that, </font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana"
 size="2">"any musical value heard [in the cylinder recording] can be charitably
          </font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">described
  as the product of a pathological imagination."</font></big></big><br>
             <big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">Indeed, despite various
  attempts at filtering and enhancing the recording, </font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2">the poor quality of the cylinder recording resulted 
  in a general concensus </font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2">that the recording was of no significant musicological
  value.</font></big></big><br>
             <big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">Using an innovative
approach   to audio signal analysis (see <a href="paper1.html">Berger, Coifman
and</a></font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2"><a
 href="paper1.html"> Goldberg, 1994</a>) PhD candidate   Charles Nichols
and I were able to transcribe the</font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"> music by painstakingly removing layers of noise 
  to reveal the music embedded</font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"> within. </font></big></big><br>
             <big><big><font face="Verdana" size="2">Transcription was followed 
  by careful analysis of the numerous</font></big></big><big><big><font
 face="Verdana" size="2"> performance nuances, agogic inflections, improvised 
  segments and added </font></big></big><big><big><font face="Verdana"
 size="2">elaborations.</font></big></big><br>
            <br>
          <br>
          <br>
          <br>
             </div>
                                                 
        <table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" border="0" width="100%">
              <tbody>
                <tr>
